Colorizing Lunch atop a Skyscraper

May 13, 2021 • Gabriel Leuzinger • 1 min read

New York   1930s   skyscraper

One of New York most iconic photos

Lunch atop a Skyscraper is certainly one of the most famous photos of all time. It is the Corbis photo agency’s most reproduced image. For a company that also owned images of 20th century icons like Albert Einstein and Martin Luther King Jr., that’s really impressive!!

The photograph was taken on September 20, 1932, on the 69th floor of the RCA Building during the last months of construction. Although the the photo was pre-arranged by Rockfeller Center to promote its newest skyscraper, these are real ironworkers more than 250 meters(!!) above Manhattan. There were no Hollywood special effects or camera tricks here. However, John Anderson argued that the photo was not so dangeorus. According to him, there was a perfectly safe and finished floor below the men, but out of the picture.

Little is known about the people involved in this masterpiece, despite its fame. There is uncertainty about who took the picture, althouhg it was recently credited to Charles C. Ebbets. Besides, only two of the ironworkers were identified: Joseph Eckner (the third from the left) and Joe Curtis (third from the right). The names of the other nine men are still unknown.

Therefore, I decided to use this iconic picture in my project. I use Jason Antic's De-Oldify code which is a deep learning based project to colorize and restore old images and film footage. In case you are interested, you can check out the project here.

The image used in this project was retrieved from Wikipedia.

The quality of the colorized photo is really impressive, don't you think? I could find only a few spots were the colors looked odd. Congratulations to mr. Antic!!

I hope you enjoyed this project as much as I did!
